   <titles>
      <title>The Dilation Transformations</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>The counterclockwise rotation of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math> about the origin through the angle <math>
                     <latex>\theta</latex>
                  </math> is given by </para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>
					
R_{\theta}\from \RNr[2] \longrightarrow \RNr[2],\quad R_{\theta}(x,y) = 
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
\cos\theta &amp; -\sin\theta \\
\sin\theta &amp; \cos\theta
\end{array}
\right]
\left[
\begin{array}{r} x \\ y \end{array}
\right]
					
				</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>To understand where this matrix comes from, consider the picture below</para.body>
            </para>
            <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
               <img xmlns="" src="ims/Rotation.png"/>
            </media>
            <para>
               <para.body>Both <math>
                     <latex>R(\StdBss{1})</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>R(\StdBss{2})</latex>
                  </math> result from rotating <math>
                     <latex>\StdBss{1}</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\StdBss{2}</latex>
                  </math> counterclockwise about the origin through the angle <math>
                     <latex>\theta</latex>
                  </math>. So they are vectors of length <math>
                     <latex>1</latex>
                  </math>. Therefore the coordinates of these vectors are as indicated.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
